{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "Credit card companies have upended the business model of sex traffickers by eliminating a way they pay for advertising.", "abstract": "Nicholas Kristof Op-Ed column commends American Express, Visa and MasterCard for making it far more difficult for pimps to use credit cards to pay for prostitution ads, striking welcome blow to human trafficking; observes that notorious website Backpage.com is able to continue serving ads despite history of teenage girls being sold there due to loophole in federal law; observes that America cannot besmirch human trafficking abroad until it cleans up its own act at home.  ", "section_name": "Opinion", "print_page": "27", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"firstname": "Nicholas", "role": "reported", "lastname": "KRISTOF", "rank": 1, "organization": ""}], "original": "By NICHOLAS KRISTOF"}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/06/opinion/nicholas-kristof-making-life-harder-for-pimps.html", "lead_paragraph": "Credit card companies have upended the business model of sex traffickers by eliminating a way they pay for advertising.", "headline": {"print_headline": "Making Life  Harder  for Pimps", "main": "Making Life Harder for Pimps", "content_kicker": "Op-Ed Columnist", "kicker": "Op-Ed Columnist"}, "_id": "55c30ae738f0d81c4b043bd6", "word_count": "819", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2015/08/06/opinion/06kristof-Web/06kristof-Web-thumbWide.jpg", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2015/08/06/opinion/06kristof-Web/06kristof-Web-thumbWide.jpg", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 409, "url": "images/2015/08/06/opinion/06kristof-Web/06kristof-Web-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2015/08/06/opinion/06kristof-Web/06kristof-Web-articleLarge.jpg", "xlargewidth": "600", "xlargeheight": "409"}, "subtype": "xlarge", "width": 600, "type": "image"}, {"height": 75, "url": "images/2015/08/06/opinion/06k